The dollar remained firmed against other major  currencies in quiet trading here Friday after the government reported an  unexpectedly small rise in April consumer prices and because of a long holiday  weekend in Europe.
Gold, meanwhile, rose to 380.70 dollars an ounce, up .80 cents from late  Thursday.
At about 16:55 a.m. (2055 GMT), the greenback traded at 1.6695 German  marks, unchanged from mid-day and up from 1.6675 late Thursday.
The US currency also firmed against other major European currencies,  rising to 5.7260 French francs from 5.7200 late Thursday, 1.4260 Swiss francs  (1.4245). Against the pound sterling it stood at 0.6671 (0.6669).
Traders were cautiously awaiting the Federal Reserve's next meeting of its  policy-setting Open Market Committee, on Tuesday. Analysts expect the Fed will  raise the federal funds rate, the interest charged on overnight interbank  loans.
